## What is the OSI Model?

OSI stands for Open Systems Interconnection. It is a 7-layer framework that describes exactly how data travels from one device to another across a network. Every networking professional, security analyst, and hacker uses this model to communicate clearly about where in a system something is happening.

Why it matters for cybersecurity: Every single attack targets a specific layer. Knowing the layer tells you what tool to use, how to defend it, and how to explain it to a client or employer.

Memory trick: All People Seem To Need Data Processing
(Application → Presentation → Session → Transport → Network → Data Link → Physical)

---

## The 7 Layers — Complete Reference

---

### Layer 7 — Application
What it does: The layer users interact with directly. This is where software communicates with the network.

Real-world protocols:
- HTTP / HTTPS — web browsing
- DNS — translating domain names to IP addresses
- FTP — file transfer
- SMTP — sending email
- SSH — secure remote terminal access

Security attacks at this layer:
- SQL Injection — injecting malicious database commands into web forms
- Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) — injecting malicious scripts into web pages
- Phishing — deceptive emails that trick users
- DNS Poisoning — corrupting DNS to redirect traffic to malicious servers
- Directory Traversal — accessing unauthorized files on a web server

Business relevance: Web application attacks happen at Layer 7. 90% of data breaches involve Layer 7 vulnerabilities. Every company with a website needs Layer 7 security.

---

### Layer 6 — Presentation
What it does: Translates data between the network and the application. Handles encryption, decryption, and data formatting so both sides can understand each other.

Real-world examples:
- TLS/SSL encryption — encrypts HTTPS traffic
- JPEG, PNG, MP4 — file format translation
- ASCII, Unicode — character encoding

Security attacks at this layer:
- SSL Stripping — forcing a secure HTTPS connection to downgrade to unencrypted HTTP
- Padding Oracle attacks — exploiting flaws in encryption implementation

Business relevance: Every company transmitting sensitive data (credit cards, health records, logins) depends on Layer 6 encryption. Compliance frameworks like PCI-DSS and HIPAA require proper Layer 6 protection.

---

### Layer 5 — Session
What it does: Establishes, manages, and terminates communication sessions between applications. Keeps track of which conversation is which when multiple connections are open simultaneously.

Real-world examples:
- Login sessions on websites
- NetBIOS — Windows session management
- RPC (Remote Procedure Call) — used in enterprise applications

Security attacks at this layer:
- Session Hijacking — stealing an authenticated session token to impersonate a logged-in user
- Session Fixation — forcing a user to use a known session ID so the attacker can take over

Business relevance: Every web application that has user logins uses Layer 5 sessions. Weak session management is one of the OWASP Top 10 most critical web vulnerabilities.

---

### Layer 4 — Transport
What it does: Manages end-to-end communication between devices. Breaks data into segments, assigns port numbers, and controls whether delivery is reliable (TCP) or fast (UDP).

Two key protocols:

TCP (Transmission Control Protocol)
- Reliable — guarantees every packet arrives
- Ordered — packets arrive in the correct sequence
- Connection-oriented — requires a handshake before data flows
- Used for: web browsing, email, SSH, file transfers
- Three-way handshake: SYN → SYN-ACK → ACK

UDP (User Datagram Protocol)
- Unreliable — no guarantee of delivery
- No handshake — just sends data immediately
- Faster than TCP
- Used for: video streaming, DNS, VoIP, online gaming

Security attacks at this layer:
- Port Scanning — probing a system to find open ports (reconnaissance)
- SYN Flood — sending thousands of SYN packets to exhaust server resources (DoS attack)
- UDP Flood — overwhelming a server with UDP packets
- Firewall bypass techniques — crafting packets to evade security rules

Business relevance: Firewalls operate primarily at Layer 4, filtering traffic by port number and protocol. Every network security architecture starts here.

---

### Layer 3 — Network
What it does: Handles logical addressing and routing. Determines the best path for data to travel from source to destination across multiple networks.

Real-world protocols:
- IP (Internet Protocol) — assigns and routes IP addresses
- ICMP — used by ping and traceroute
- OSPF, BGP — routing protocols that determine network paths

IP Address basics:
- IPv4: 32-bit address — example: 192.168.1.1
- IPv6: 128-bit address — example: 2001:0db8:85a3::8a2e:0370:7334
- Public IP: visible on the internet
- Private IP: used inside local networks (192.168.x.x, 10. x.x.x, 172.16.x.x)

Security attacks at this layer:
- IP Spoofing — forging the source IP address to disguise the attacker's identity
- DDoS (Distributed Denial of Service) — flooding a target with traffic from thousands of sources
- Man-in-the-Middle (routing) — intercepting traffic between two hosts
- ICMP Flood (Ping Flood) — overwhelming a target with ping requests

Business relevance: Network segmentation (separating sensitive systems from public networks) is a fundamental Layer 3 security control. Required by nearly every compliance framework.

---

### Layer 2 — Data Link
What it does: Handles communication between devices on the SAME local network. Uses MAC (Media Access Control) addresses to identify devices. Controls how data is placed on and received from the physical medium.

Real-world examples:
- Ethernet — the standard wired LAN protocol
- Wi-Fi (802.11) — wireless LAN
- Switches — Layer 2 devices that forward frames by MAC address
- ARP (Address Resolution Protocol) — maps IP addresses to MAC addresses

Security attacks at this layer:
- ARP Spoofing/Poisoning — attacker sends fake ARP replies to link their MAC to a legitimate IP, enabling man-in-the-middle attacks
- MAC Flooding — overwhelming a switch's MAC address table to force it into hub mode, making traffic visible to all
- VLAN Hopping — exploiting misconfigured VLANs to access traffic on other network segments

Business relevance: Internal network threats (insider attacks, compromised devices) operate at Layer 2. Switch security configurations and VLAN segmentation are Layer 2 defenses required in enterprise environments.

---

### Layer 1 — Physical
What it does: The actual physical transmission of raw bits (1s and 0s) over a medium. This includes everything you can physically touch or see.

Real-world examples:
- Ethernet cables (Cat5e, Cat6)
- Fiber optic cables
- Wi-Fi radio signals
- Bluetooth signals
- Network interface cards (NICs)
- Hubs, repeaters

Security attacks at this layer:
- Wiretapping — physically intercepting cable traffic
- Signal Jamming — disrupting wireless communications
- Hardware Keyloggers — physical devices that record keystrokes
- Rogue Access Points — unauthorized Wi-Fi devices that intercept wireless traffic
- Cable cutting — physically severing network connections (sabotage)

Business relevance: Physical security is the first line of defense. Data center security (locked racks, access control), cable management, and preventing unauthorized physical access are all Layer 1 concerns.

