## Hands-On Practice Done Today

Kali Linux terminal command:
```
ping google.com
```
Result: Received ICMP echo replies from 142.250.x.x
What this proves: ping uses ICMP, which operates at Layer 3 (Network layer). The OS resolved the domain name using DNS (Layer 7) before sending the ping.

What I observed: Even a simple ping command uses multiple OSI layers simultaneously — Layer 7 for DNS, Layer 3 for ICMP, Layer 2 for the Ethernet frame, Layer 1 for the physical WiFi signal.

---

## Key Takeaways

1. The OSI model is a universal language — every cybersecurity professional worldwide uses these 7 layers to communicate about network problems and attacks
2. Attacks do not stay in one layer — a successful attack often involves multiple layers simultaneously
3. Defense in depth means protecting every layer — not just Layer 7 (the application)
4. As a SOC analyst, when an alert fires, you immediately ask: Which layer is this attack targeting? That tells you which tool to use and how to respond
5. As a penetration tester, you systematically test each layer, looking for weaknesses

